The article discusses the historical significance of the march from Selma, Alabama to secure the right to vote and the subsequent passage of the Voting Rights Act of 1965. It highlights the impact of the Shelby County Supreme Court decision in 2013, which weakened the Voting Rights Act and led to a new assault on voting rights in recent years. The article emphasizes the need to protect the freedom to vote and calls on Congress to pass federal legislation and implement President Joe Biden's Executive Order on Promoting Access to Voting. It concludes by urging readers to continue fighting to secure and safeguard the freedom to vote as a way of honoring the legacy of those who marched in Selma.